# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2005-australian-football-international-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] The **2002 Australian Football International Cup** was the inaugural international Australian rules football tournament held in Melbourne, Australia in 2002.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] 11 nations participated from around the world and the tournament was officiated by the International Australian Football Council.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the tournament, finishing undefeated and victorious over Papua New Guinea in the Grand Final on 23 August at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] A 22 player All-International squad was named, however names were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] The **2005 AFL season** was the 109th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] The season featured sixteen clubs, ran from 24 March until 24 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top eight clubs.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] The premiership was won by the Sydney Swans for the fourth time, after they defeated West Coast by four points in the AFL Grand Final.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] It was the club's first premiership since it won the 1933 premiership as South Melbourne, and ended a 72-year premiership drought which stands as the longest in league history.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) percentage; 3) number of points for.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in green indicate that the team finished the round inside the top 8.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in blue indicates the team finished first on the ladder in that round.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in red indicates the team finished in last place on the ladder in that round.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] Additionally, Michael Voss (Brisbane Lions) played his 250th AFL game and Mal Michael his 100th club game for the Lions, both also against the Swans, in round 3.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-afl-season] The Swans won the premiership despite being ranked 14th in scoring during the regular season, their 1,974 points scored for being 42 points less than wooden-spooners Carlton which scored 2,016 points from their twenty-two matches, and 15th in total possessions.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The **2005 Australian Football International Cup** was the second time that the Australian Football International Cup tournament, an international Australian rules football competition was held.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The event was hosted by both Melbourne and Wangaratta, Australia, in 2005.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] 10 nations participated following the late withdrawal of both Nauru and Denmark and the introduction of Spain.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] All sides were scheduled to play 4 games, after which the top 4 sides played off in semi-finals for a berth in the Grand Final decider.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was between Papua New Guinea and New Zealand.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Both sides went through the tournament undefeated.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] It was played as a curtain raiser to an official Australian Football League premiership season match and was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand were crowned international champions for the first time.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The grand final was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The best and fairest medal was awarded to New Zealand's James Bowden.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Like the All-Australian Team in the Australian Football League, a team selected from the best players in the International Cup was selected.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Team members were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The **2011 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup 2011** or **IC11**) was the fourth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 12 and 27 August 2011 by 18 nations, with games played in both Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Two matches were played as curtain raisers to AFL premiership matches, USA vs South Africa at Stadium Australia and the IC Grand Final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won its second men's championship, and the inaugural women's championship (Ryan Aslett Cup).
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] 17 of these clubs represented single nations, and one (the Peres Team for Peace) represented both Israel and the Palestinian Territories.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The first round of matches was played with modified rules, most significantly the reduction of game length to two-quarters, in the same manner as the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, the best two teams from each Group were regrouped into four groups of three teams, based on Win-Draw-Loss performance and Percentage in Round 1, all within a larger group known as Division 1.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would remain in contention for the International Cup title.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining six were regrouped in the same way, into two subgroups of Division 2.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would compete for a secondary prize.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 1 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 2 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups, as well as a single "cross-over" match against a team in the opposite group.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 2, the teams were once again re-seeded based on their performance in the previous round; the teams in Division 1 were seeded in positions 1-12, and the teams in Division 2 in positions 13–18.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These matches were played at the same time as the final round 2 Division 2 matches; the Division 2 teams did not participate in this round.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] In the opening round of the Women's International Cup, the five teams played each other once, over the course of 10 days.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, Australia, the lowest ranked team in the competition based on points and percentage, was eliminated and finished in 5th place.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining four clubs will compete in the finals.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The **2014 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2014 or **IC14**) was the fifth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between Saturday August 9 to Saturday August 23, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] There are 18 nations competing in the 2014 Tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Of these, 15 competed in the previous tournament; Indonesia and Pakistan make their debuts, while Finland return having previously competed in 2008.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The teams were seeded into three pools of six to decide which teams would play each other, though all teams will be ranked on a single ladder.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The top four teams at the end of Day 3 progress to the International Cup Semi-finals.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other teams will play another match, depending on their ladder position, with those results added to the Ladder to decide Day 5 matchups.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The 5th to 12th-placed teams will play in Division 1 for the remainder of the tournament, and the 13th-placed team onwards will play in Division 2.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] For the second consecutive time, there was a concurrent Women's tournament alongside the Men's competition.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Seven teams participated from five countries - the United States and Canada both fielded two teams.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Each team played four matches across five matchdays.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Matches played on Saturday 16 August - the "Community Round" of the tournament - were played as curtain-raisers to other amateur Metropolitan and Country football matches to be confirmed; all other games in the round-robin were held at Royal Park, Melbourne.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] After the round-robin tournament, the last placed team was eliminated.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other six teams played one extra match to decide the final placings, with the top two teams on the ladder playing in the Women's International Cup Grand Final.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The **2017 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2017 or IC17) was the sixth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, a triennial international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 5–19 August 2017, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous men's tournament champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Previous women's winners (Ireland and Canada) also competed in the tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea achieved its 3rd men's title and Ireland achieved its 2nd women's title.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 AFL International Cup was played in Melbourne from 5 to 19 August, with 18 men's teams and eight women's teams competing.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The European Crusaders was a combined team made up of women from Britain, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Poland and Sweden.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] In the table below, the numbers in parentheses refer to the team's Unofficial World Rankings by *World Footy News* prior to the competition.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's fixture was played across two divisions.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Division One played four matches against other teams within the division and were ranked from one to ten, with finals to follow between the top two placed teams on the ladder, the third and fourth placed teams, and so on.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's Division Two competition and the women's competition saw teams split into two pools of four with each team playing matches against the three opponents in their pool before competing in semi-finals and grand finals based on finishing positions within the pool.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The women's grand final was played at Etihad Stadium as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 clash between Carlton and Hawthorn.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's grand final was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 match between Collingwood and Geelong.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The majority of the matches were played at Royal Park in the Melbourne suburb of Parkville.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The inclusion of a "Community Round" allowed matches to be played as curtain-raisers to local suburban, amateur and country matches.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally, the International Cup introduced a "School Round" to be played on 9 August, with games played at suburban and country schools.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Fixtures for the tournament were released by the AFL on 18 July 2017.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:2005-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
